  "name": "Morrison VAD Hemolysis CFD Credibility Package — Minimal Profile",
  "description": "This package documents credibility evidence for a CFD-based hemolysis prediction model applied to the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump. The model has been applied in clinical research contexts to inform ventricular assist device design decisions. Computational predictions of the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) were generated using a power-law damage accumulation model coupled to a steady-state RANS solver. Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation was performed across rheological and geometric input parameters. All thirteen ASME V&V 40 credibility factors were reviewed; seven were formally assessed and six were flagged as epistemic gaps at the prevailing model risk level. This assessment package conforms to the Minimal profile and relies on structured credibility factor records and a decision record to satisfy body requirements; no structured Context of Use object is included, as the intended-use scope is conveyed through narrative description alone.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/vad-hemolysis-cfd-mrl5",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/vad-hemolysis-nih-prediction",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/cfd-hemolysis-powerlaw-rans",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-piv-benchmark",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/hemolysis-in-vitro-nih-measurements"
  ],
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/nih-comparison-operating-point-a",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "NIH prediction vs. in-vitro measurement at nominal VAD operating point"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/velocity-field-piv-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Velocity field comparison against FDA pump PIV benchmark dataset"
    }
  ],
  "wasDerivedFrom": "https://doi.org/10.1115/1.4041290",
